revision.text:
'''Agathangelos''' (in {{lang-xcl|Ագաթանգեղոս}} Agatʿangełos, in [[Greek language|Greek]] {{lang|grc|Ἀγαθάγγελος}} "bearer of good news" or angel, {{circa}} 4th<ref name="EB">Encyclopædia Britannica: a new survey of universal knowledge: Volume 2- 1961, p. 383.</ref> or 5th<ref>The Armenians Anne Elizabeth Redgate - 2000 - Page 122.</ref> centuries AD) was a supposed secretary of [[Tiridates III of Armenia|Tiridates III]], King of [[Armenia]], under whose name there has come down a life of the first apostle of Armenia, [[Gregory the Illuminator]], who died about 332.<ref name="EB"/><ref>Who's who in Christianity - Lavinia Cohn-Sherbok - 1998 - p. 113 - Gregory the Illuminator (c. 240-332).</ref> It purports to exhibit the deeds and discourses of Gregory, and has reached us in [[Armenian language|Armenian]] and in [[Greek language|Greek]]. The text of this history has been considerably altered, but it has always been in high favor with the Armenians.<ref name="EB1911">{{EB1911|inline=1|wstitle=Agathangelus|volume=1|page=370}}</ref> [[Alfred von Gutschmid|Von Gutschmid]] maintains that the unknown author made use of a genuine life of St. Gregory, also of a history of his [[martyr]]dom and of that of Saint [[Rhipsime]] and her companions. Historical facts are intermingled in this life with [[legend]]ary or uncertain additions, and the whole is woven into a certain unity by the narrator, who may have assumed his significant name from his quality of narrator of "the good news" of Armenia's conversion.<ref>{{Catholic Encyclopedia |inline=1 |wstitle=Agathangelus}}</ref> It has been translated into several languages, and [[Greek language|Greek]] and [[Latin language|Latin]] translations are found in the ''Acta Sanctorum Bollandistarum'', tome viii.<ref name="EB1911"/>

According to Agathangelos, he was tasked by Tiridates III to write about his father [[Khosrov II of Armenia]] and his reign period. Until the 19th century, based on this fact, scholars believe that Agatangelos lived in the 4th century. However further detailed research of his writing has demonstrated that Agathangelos lived and worked in the 5th century and was not able to be Tiridates III's secretary.

