[[File:BruecknerAlexander1834-1896.jpg|right|thumb|Alexander Bruckner]] '''Alexander Brückner''' (5 August 1834, [[Saint Petersburg]] &ndash; 15 November 1896, [[Jena]]) was a Baltic German historian who specialized in [[Russian history|Russian studies]]. He was the father of [[geographer]] [[Eduard Brückner]].
He studied history and economics at the universities of [[University of Heidelberg|Heidelberg]], [[University of Jena|Jena]] and [[University of Berlin|Berlin]], receiving his doctorate in Heidelberg with a dissertation on the history of the [[Diet of Worms|Diet of Worms (1521)]]. As a student, his instructors included [[Johann Gustav Droysen]], [[Ludwig Häusser]], [[Leopold von Ranke]] and [[Friedrich von Raumer]]. From 1861 to 1867 he served as a professor of history at the Imperial Law School in St. Petersburg, and afterwards was a professor of history at the universities of [[University of Odessa|Odessa]] (from 1867) and [[University of Dorpat|Dorpat]] (1872–1891).<ref>[https://de.wikisource.org/wiki/ADB:Br%C3%BCckner,_Alexander ADB:Brückner, Alexander] at [[Allgemeine Deutsche Biographie]]</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=qBwoAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA55&lpg=PA55&dq=%22Br%C3%BCckner,+Alexander%22+1834&source=bl&ots=DljBsXWhoH&sig=Aveb0IIdfRdLHCa2pxH4dsXpwkI&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiGs56pxP3JAhVELSYKHVTRBfEQ6AEIQTAG#v=onepage&q=%22Br%C3%BCckner%2C%20Alexander%22%201834&f=false New International Encyclopedia, Volume 4] Google Books</ref>
== Selected works == Bruckner was fluent in both German and Russian, and authored works in both languages. The following are a list of some of his German writings: * ''Das Kupfergeld 1856-63 in Russland'', 1863 &ndash; Copper money in Russia, 1856–63. * ''Culturhistorische Studien'', 1878 &ndash; Cultural history studies. * ''Peter der Grosse'', 1879 &ndash; [[Peter the Great]]. * ''Katharina die Zweite'', 1883 &ndash; [[Catherine the Great]]. * ''Die Europäisierung Russlands Land und Volk'', 1888 &ndash; The Europeanization of Russia's country and people. * ''Geschichte Russlands bis zum Ende des 18 Jahrhunderts'', (2 volumes, 1896–1913), with Constantin Mettig &ndash; History of Russia until the end of the 18th century.<ref>[http://www.worldcat.org/identities/lccn-no92-29763/ Most widely held works by Alexander Brückner] WorldCat Identities</ref>
