'''Latifa Lakhdar''' (born 1 February 1956) is a [[Tunisia]]n [[historian]] and [[politician]] who was Minister of Culture from February 2015 until January 2016.
==Early life and education== Lakhdar was born in [[Zarzis]] on 1 February 1956. She was a student of [[Mohamed Arkoun]] at the [[Sorbonne]] in [[Paris]].<ref name=other>{{cite web|title=The Other Islam: Scholarly, and Written with a Sharp Pen|first=Sandro|last=Magister|work=Chiesa|url=http://chiesa.espresso.repubblica.it/articolo/6888?eng=y|date=19 November 2002|accessdate=4 December 2016}}</ref>
==Career== Lakhdar was Professor of Contemporary History at [[University of Ez-Zitouna]] from 1991–1999 and from 2000–2015 at the [[University of Tunis]].<ref name=qui>{{cite web|language=French|url=http://www.tekiano.com/2015/01/24/qui-est-latifa-lakhdhar-nouvelle-ministre-de-la-culture/|title=Qui est Latifa Lakhdhar, nouvelle ministre de la Culture?|date=24 January 2015|accessdate=4 December 2016|work=Tekiano}}</ref>
Lakhdar is an expert in Islamic thought<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hebdo.ahram.org.eg/NewsContent/0/8/27/10114/Latifa-Lakhdar--L’esprit-critique-tunisien-va-évol.aspx|title=Latifa Lakhdar : L’esprit critique tunisien va évoluer |language=French|work=Al-Ahram|date=15 April 2015|accessdate=4 December 2016|first=Karem|last=Yéhia}}</ref><ref name=Bardo/> and has published several books in [[Arabic]] and [[French language|French]], notably on the condition of women in Islamic societies.<ref name=other/><ref name=qui/> She is a [[women's rights activist]] and [[secularist]].<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.bakerinstitute.org/files/8153/|title=What is democracy? Promises and perils of the Arab Spring|first=Valetine M.|last=Moghadam|year=2013|journal=Current Sociology|pages=393–408}}</ref> She has argued that [[Islamic fundamentalism]], including [[Islamic terrorism]] is part of [[Orthodox Islam|Islamic orthodoxy]], but that Islamic thought can be enlightened and liberal if it undergoes a "critical revolution".<ref name=other/> She argues that "The jihadist idea that religion should rule politics is a model that never existed."<ref name=Bardo/>
===Political career=== Lakhdar is a founding member of the [[Association tunisienne des femmes démocrates]]. In 2011, she was elected Vice-President of the [[Higher Authority for Realisation of the Objectives of the Revolution, Political Reform and Democratic Transition]].<ref name=qui/><ref>{{cite book|page=43|title=Making Globalization Work for Women: The Role of Social Rights and Trade Union Leadership|year=2011|publisher=SUNY Press|first1=Valentine M.|last1=Moghadam|first2=Suzanne|last2=Franzway|first3=Mary Margaret|last3=Fonow|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=_HoeAwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>
On 6 February 2015, Lakhdar was appointed Minister of Culture and Heritage Preservation, as an [[Independent politician|independent]], in the government of Prime Minister [[Habib Essid]].<ref name=tekiano/> She was in communication with museum staff during the [[Bardo National Museum attack]] on 18 March 2015 and later unveiled a memorial at the site.<ref name=Bardo>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/news/world/middle-east/tunisian-minister-followed-bardo-attack-from-crisis-cell-1.2150533|work=Irish Times|title=Tunisian minister followed Bardo attack from ‘crisis cell’|first=Lara|last=Marlowe|date=24 March 2015|accessdate=4 December 2016}}</ref>
On February 12, 2016, Lakhdar was made a Commander of the [[Order of the Republic (Tunisia)|Order of the Republic]] by President [[Béji Caïd Essebsi]] for her service.<ref name=tekiano>{{cite web|url=http://www.tekiano.com/2016/02/12/tunisie-latifa-lakhdar-decoree-des-insignes-de-commandeur-de-lordre-de-la-republique-video/|title=Tunisie : Latifa Lakhdar décorée des insignes de commandeur de l’ordre de la République|language=French|date=12 February 2016|accessdate=4 December 2016|work=Tekiano}}</ref>
