{{Use Australian English|date=November 2016}} {{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}} {{Infobox person | name = Maria Tumarkin | nationality = Australian | occupation = author, cultural historian, and professor of writing }}
'''Maria Tumarkin''' is an Australian author, cultural historian, and professor of writing at the [[University of Melbourne]].<ref>[http://www.abc.net.au/radionational/programs/booksandarts/why-this-american-life-falls-short-for-writer-maria-tumarkin/5635986 ABC Australia, Thursday 31 July 2014: "Why This American Life falls short for writer Maria Tumarkin"]</ref><ref name="theage1">{{citation |title=Traumascapes, 23 July 2005 |periodical=The Age |url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/reviews/traumascapes/2005/07/22/1121539136248.html |first=Charlotte |last=Wood}}</ref>
==Biography== Tumarkin was originally born and raised in Kharkov in the Ukraine.<ref name="theage" >{{citation |title=Traumascapes |date=23 July 2005 |periodical=[[The Age]] |url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/reviews/traumascapes/2005/07/22/1121539136248.html |first=Charlotte |last=Wood}}</ref> She "left the Ukraine as part of the Jewish emigration in 1989 when she was a teenager." <ref name="otherland" >[http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/books/otherland-a-journey-with-my-daughter-20100419-soaa.html| ''Otherland: A Journey with My Daughter'', 19 April 2010, [[Sydney Morning Herald]], Robert Dessaix]</ref> She holds a BA (Hons) and a PhD in cultural history from the University of Melbourne.
All three of her books were shortlisted for literary prizes—most recently, ''Otherland'' was shortlisted for the [[Victorian Premier's Literary Awards]], The Age Book of the Year, and [[NSW Premier’s Literary Award]]. Her essay, "No Skin," was one of five finalists for the 2015 Melbourne Prize in Writing for essays shorter than 20,000 words.<ref name="MelbournePrize" >{{citation |title=Five writers vie for $60,000 Melbourne Prize |date=2 September 2015 |accessdate=11 July 2016 |periodical=[[Sydney Morning Herald]] |url=http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/books/five-writers-vie-for-60000-melbourne-prize-20150902-gjcdkd.html |first=Jason|last=Steger}}</ref><ref name="Essays">[http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/books/where-are-all-the-great-australian-essays-20160220-gmxuh7.html| ''Where are all the great Australian essays?'', 24 February 2016, [[Sydney Morning Herald]]]</ref>
==Books== * ''[[Traumascapes|Traumascapes: The Power and Fate of Places Transformed by Tragedy]]'' (2005) * ''Courage'' (2007) * ''Otherland: A Journey With My Daughter'' (2010) * ''Axiomatic'' (2018)
