'''Nikita Vasilyevich Petrov''' ({{lang-ru|Ники́та Васи́льевич Петро́в}}, born 31 January 1957, Kiev) is a [[Russia]]n [[historian]]. He works at ''[[Memorial (society)|Memorial]],'' a Russian organization dedicated to studying Soviet political repression. Petrov specializes in [[Soviet security service]]s.<ref>[http://memo.ru/d/3409.html "Никита Васильевич Петров"] at the ''Memorial'' website</ref>

The book about  [[Nikolai Ezhov]] written by Nikita Petrov and Marc Jansen is based on the archives made accessible after the [[dissolution of the Soviet Union]]. Petrov's part was tracking original archival documents, while Jansen worked with published sources.

On March 24, 2005 Nikita Petrov was awarded Knight's Cross of the [[Order of Merit of the Republic of Poland]] for his efforts in uncovering truth about repressions against [[Polish people]] during the war.<ref>[http://isap.sejm.gov.pl/DetailsServlet?id=WMP20050430594 Rej. 60/2005: Postanowienie Prezydenta Rzeczypospolitej Polskiej z dnia 24 marca 2005 r. o nadaniu orderów]</ref>

In 2008 Petrov earned Ph.D. from the [[University of Amsterdam]] (Instituut voor Cultuur en Geschiedenis, Faculty of Humanities) with the thesis "Сталин и органы НКВД-МГБ в советизации стран Центральной и Восточной Европы. 1945–1953 гг."<ref>[http://dare.uva.nl/record/1/392553 Сталин и органы НКВД-МГБ в советизации стран Центральной и Восточной Европы. 1945–1953 гг. : Stalinisme en Sovjetisering 1945-1953 : Een studie van archiefmateriaal over Stalin, de NKVD-MGB, Duitsland en andere landen in Centraal- en Oost-Europa], UvA-DARE (Digital Academic Repository)</ref>

Articles by Petrov were published in the ''[[Novaya Gazeta]]''.<ref>{{cite news|author=Петров, Никита|title=Материалы автора|trans-title=Author's materials|url=http://www.novayagazeta.ru/profile/3867/|work=[[Novaya Gazeta]]|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151119110159/http://www.novayagazeta.ru/profile/3867|archivedate=2015-11-19|df=}}</ref>

